            <person xml:id="pers1159">
               <p>The daughter of a <placeName>West India</placeName> merchant resident in
                     <placeName>Bristol</placeName>, Elizabeth (&quot;Betsy&quot;) was disinherited
                  by her father when she joined the Methodists. She remained single, living on an
                  annuity bequeathed by her uncle. Elizabeth&apos;s home on <placeName>Hilgrove
                     Street</placeName> was a center of Methodism in the city of
                     <placeName>Bristol</placeName> and she was a described by <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> as &quot;deep in grace, and
                  lives like an angel here below.&quot; Johnson was one of the Methodists opposed to
                  separation from the Church of <placeName>England</placeName>. See <hi
                     rend="italic">An Account of Elizabeth Johnson</hi>
                     (<placeName>Bristol</placeName>: Pine, <date when="1799">1799</date>).</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
